    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-02-23T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-02-23T19:00:00-05:00" n="537"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d537">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.31/2–2351: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassies in France and Italy</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d537fn1">Repeated to the U.S. Delegation at Torquay as
                        402.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-02-23T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 23, 1951—7 p. m</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4442 [Paris] and 3748 [Rome].</p>
                <p>1. US interest in reducing disparities in <gloss target="#t_Eur1">Eur</gloss>
                    tariff levels on a non-preferential basis outlined Circ <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 413 Jan 22, and <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 316, Jan 15 to Torquay. Strongly endorse,
                    therefore, suggestion that Emba Paris and Rome again approach govts along lines
                    described para 4 of reftel.</p>
                <p>2. In making point contained para 4a of reftel, you may wish to note that there
                    has been inadequate time at Torquay for effective <gloss target="#t_GATT1"
                        >GATT</gloss> contribution to solution European tariff problem. Ref para 4b
                    of reftel, suggest you give positive formulation of this point, stressing
                    importance of progress in meeting <gloss target="#t_Eur1">Eur</gloss> tariff
                    problem to continued success of the <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss> trade
                    liberalization program.</p>
                <p>3. For info Rome, assume you are aware that <gloss target="#t_OEEC1">OEEC</gloss>
                    Council decision of Oct 27, 1950 on 75% liberalization made contingent on
                    progress in reducing <gloss target="#t_Eur1">Eur</gloss> tariff disparities at
                    Torquay.</p>
                <p>For purposes your discussion with Italians, we note that at Torquay (Torquay 453,
                    rptd Rome 10) Italians consider progress in <gloss target="#t_Eur1">Eur</gloss>
                    integration prerequisite to reduction tariff disparities. Seems clear that
                    reduction in tariff disparities can equally or better be considered prerequisite
                    to <gloss target="#t_Eur1">Eur</gloss> econ integration.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
